AUBER AI Agent Workshop

AUBER AI Agent Workshop

Overview

From Data to Narrative: AI Agents for Regional Economic Analysis

Pre-Conference Workshop for AUBER

This hands-on session introduces participants to building a lightweight AI agent that combines public data with generative AI to produce county-level population change narratives and visualizes them on an interactive map. Youll learn how to use R to pull Census data, craft structured prompts for LLMs like Gemini, generate plain-language summaries and headlines for each county, and display the results as a choropleth map with rich tooltips.

Designed for economists, policy analysts, and research center staff, this session provides a practical and replicable framework to automate and humanize regional economic insights. Whether youre new to LLMs or already exploring AI workflows, youll walk away with working code, new ideas, and a story-driven approach to your data.

By the end of this workshop, participants will be able to:

  • Understand how to access and extract data via APIs, using the U.S. Census Bureau as an example.
  • Apply a generative AI large language model (LLM) to interact with data iteratively and generate narrative summaries in a controlled manner.
  • Integrate these methods into a practical use case by creating state-level maps enriched with automatically generated county-level content.
  • Develop a broader perspective and process for leveraging generative AI tools to maximize impact.

Libaries & APIs

Calls the libraries and APIs (Census & Gemini) as well as allows the user to choose their desired state of interest (default set to DE given its small number of counties, this will be adjusted for MT, and any state of interest later).

library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)
library(glue)
library(gemini.R)
library(tidycensus)
library(kableExtra)
library(usethis)

# Open r environment to save API keys
#usethis::edit_r_environ()

# Set the Gemini API
setAPI(Sys.getenv("GOOGLE_GEMINI_KEY"))
# Test the API with a prompt
#gemini("Write me a joke about an economist that walks into a bar")

# Set the Census API
setAPI(Sys.getenv("CENSUS_API_KEY"))

# Set the State you would like to pull using the abbreviation and specify the name:
state_pull = "DE"
state_name = "Delaware"

Data Acquisition & Wrangling

This block leverages the tidycensus package to pull the raw population data at the county level for 2022 and 2023, and additionally pulls the component data to extract the natural change and the net migration change. After the individual data pulls, the code joins these together into a single dataset with the necessary variables needed for the final map.

# Step 1: Get 2022 population totals and changes
pop_2022_raw <- get_estimates(
  geography = "county",
  product = "population",
  vintage = 2022,
  state = state_pull
)

pop_2022 <- pop_2022_raw |>
  filter(variable %in% c("POPESTIMATE")) |>
  mutate(variable = paste0(variable, "2022")) |>
  select(GEOID, NAME, variable, value) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = variable, values_from = value)

# Step 2: Get 2023 population totals and changes
pop_2023_raw <- get_estimates(
  geography = "county",
  product = "population",
  vintage = 2023,
  state = state_pull
)

pop_2023 <- pop_2023_raw |>
  filter(variable %in% c("POPESTIMATE", "NPOPCHG")) |>
  mutate(variable = paste0(variable, "2023")) |>
  select(GEOID, NAME, variable, value) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = variable, values_from = value)

# Step 3: Get 2023 population COMPONENT totals
pop_2023_raw_comp <- get_estimates(
  geography = "county",
  product = "components",
  vintage = 2023,
  state = state_pull
)

pop_2023_comp <- pop_2023_raw_comp |>
  filter(variable %in% c("NETMIG", "NATURALCHG")) |>
  mutate(variable = paste0(variable, "2023")) |>
  select(GEOID, variable, value) |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = variable, values_from = value)

# Step 4: Merge, clean, and finalize data
countypopchange <- pop_2022 |>
  left_join(pop_2023, by = c("GEOID", "NAME"), suffix = c("_2022", "_2023")) |>
  left_join(pop_2023_comp, "GEOID") |>
  mutate(
    COUNTY = substr(GEOID, 3, 5),
    STATE = substr(GEOID, 1, 2),
    CTYNAME = gsub(" County, .*", "", NAME),
    STNAME = sub(".*, ", "", NAME),
    POPPERCENTCHANGE = ((POPESTIMATE2023 - POPESTIMATE2022) / POPESTIMATE2022) * 100) |>
  select(GEOID, COUNTY, STATE, CTYNAME, STNAME,
         POPESTIMATE2022, POPESTIMATE2023, NPOPCHG2023,
         NATURALCHG2023, NETMIG2023, POPPERCENTCHANGE)

# Preview the data
kable(head(countypopchange,3))

Base Narrative

Before leveraging the Gemini LLM to create the narrative, we need to create a new variable base_narrative that contains all the necessary information needed to include in the prompt.

statenarrative <- countypopchange |> 
  select(COUNTY, STATE, CTYNAME, STNAME, POPESTIMATE2023, POPESTIMATE2022, NPOPCHG2023, NATURALCHG2023, NETMIG2023) |>
  mutate(POPPERCENTCHANGE = ((POPESTIMATE2023-POPESTIMATE2022)/POPESTIMATE2022)*100) |> 
  mutate(GEOID = paste0(COUNTY, STATE)) |> 
  arrange(desc(POPPERCENTCHANGE)) |> 
  mutate(PCTCHANGERANK = row_number()) |> 
  mutate(base_narrative = glue(
  "County: {CTYNAME}, Population in 2023: {POPESTIMATE2023}, Population in 2022: {POPESTIMATE2022}, Population change: {NPOPCHG2023}, Percent change: {POPPERCENTCHANGE}, Percent change rank in {STNAME}: {PCTCHANGERANK}, Natural change (births vs deaths): {NATURALCHG2023}, Net migration: {NETMIG2023}"))

The Light-weight AI Agent

Creating the Narrative

Using the base_narrative, now a prompt can be constructed that is fed into a function that is sent to Gemini county by county to return the narrative. This is functionally the AI Agent.

author_role <- glue("You are a demographics journalist working to analyze data for {state_name}. Your job today is to write short -- 2-3 sentence -- summaries of population estimates from the Census Bureau for each county in the state. I will provide you the name of the county and a series of population numbers for the county. Your job is to turn it into a concise but approachable summary of what happened in that county. Here is the data you have to work with: ")

author_agent <- function(county) {
  county_narrative <- statenarrative |> filter(CTYNAME == county)
  results <- gemini(paste(author_role, county_narrative$base_narrative))
  results <- gsub("\n", "", results)
  Sys.sleep(5)
  print(paste("Processed", county_narrative$CTYNAME))
  
  # Return a single-row tibble
  tibble(county = county_narrative$CTYNAME, base_narrative = county_narrative$base_narrative, capsule_narrative = results)
}

# Set the Gemini API
setAPI(Sys.getenv("GOOGLE_GEMINI_KEY"))
gemini("Write me a haiku about the joy and sadness of being a Nebraska football fan")
##                                                                                      text 
## "Hope blooms in the fall,\nThen fades as winter descends,\nStill, we yell, \"Go Big!\"\n"
# Use map_df to directly create the final dataframe
author_agent_results <- purrr::map_df(statenarrative$CTYNAME, author_agent)
## [1] "Processed Sussex"
## [1] "Processed Kent"
## [1] "Processed New Castle"

Writing the Headlines

To make this a little more interesting, lets send the narratives that were just created back to Gemini with a a request to create a headline for the narrative for each individual county.

headline_writer_role <- "You are a headline writer. Your job is to write a short headline based on the summary given to you. This headline should be short -- it has to fit into a small space -- so bear that in mind. You are only supposed to a single headline in title case with no other text response. Here is the capsule: "

headline_agent <- function(county_input) {
  county_narrative <- author_agent_results |> filter(county == county_input)
  results <- gemini(paste(headline_writer_role, county_narrative$capsule_narrative))
  results <- gsub("\n", "", results, fixed = TRUE)
  Sys.sleep(5)
  print(paste("Processed", county_narrative$county))
  
  # Return a single-row tibble
  tibble(county = county_narrative$county, base_narrative = county_narrative$base_narrative, capsule_narrative = county_narrative$capsule_narrative, headline = results)
}

# Use map_df to directly create the final dataframe
headline_agent_results <- purrr::map_df(author_agent_results$county, headline_agent)
## [1] "Processed Sussex"
## [1] "Processed Kent"
## [1] "Processed New Castle"

Data Output

Now that the narrative and headline have been constructed, lets combine this with the previous data to include in the mapping. Additionally, this can be exported as a csv file for human review (this is a MUST.)

# Combine the agent results with key raw data measures to include in the map.
ai_agent_map_data <- headline_agent_results |>
  left_join(
    statenarrative |> select(CTYNAME, POPESTIMATE2022, POPESTIMATE2023, NPOPCHG2023,POPPERCENTCHANGE),
    by = c("county" = "CTYNAME")
  )

The Map

Leaflet Map

There are a couple of ways to approach mapping both via external software such as datawrapper, or within R itself. Here is an example using the leaflet package.

library(leaflet)
library(sf)
library(dplyr)
library(tigris)
library(htmltools)

options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE)

# --- GET GEOMETRY ---
# Automatically get FIPS code and name from state abbreviation
state_fips <- tigris::fips_codes |>
  filter(state == state_pull) |>
  distinct(state_code) |>
  pull(state_code) |>
  unique()

# Get county boundaries for that state
counties_sf <- counties(state = state_fips, cb = TRUE, year = 2023, class = "sf")

# --- MERGE DATA ---
# Join spatial geometry with AI output data
map_data <- counties_sf |>
  left_join(ai_agent_map_data, by = c("NAME" = "county"))

# --- CREATE COLOR PALETTE ---
pal <- colorNumeric("YlGnBu", domain = map_data$POPPERCENTCHANGE)

# # --- CREATE TOOLTIPS ---
# labels <- sprintf(
#   "<strong>%s County</strong><br/><b>%s</b><br/><br/>%s<br/><br/>
#    <b>2022 Population:</b> %s<br/>
#    <b>2023 Population:</b> %s<br/>
#    <b>Percent Change:</b> %.2f%%",
#   map_data$NAME,
#   map_data$headline,
#   map_data$capsule_narrative,
#   format(map_data$POPESTIMATE2022, big.mark = ","),
#   format(map_data$POPESTIMATE2023, big.mark = ","),
#   map_data$POPPERCENTCHANGE
# ) |>
#   lapply(HTML)

htmltools::tags$h2(
  paste("Population Change by County in", state_pull),
  style = "text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;"
)

Population Change by County in DE

# --- BUILD LEAFLET MAP ---
leaflet(map_data) |>
  addProviderTiles("CartoDB.Positron") |>
  addPolygons(
    fillColor = ~pal(POPPERCENTCHANGE),
    weight = 1,
    opacity = 1,
    color = "white",
    dashArray = "3",
    fillOpacity = 0.7,
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      color = "#666",
      dashArray = "",
      fillOpacity = 0.9,
      bringToFront = TRUE
    ),
   label = lapply(seq_len(nrow(map_data)), function(i) {
  HTML(sprintf(
    "<div style='width:250px; white-space:normal;'>
      <strong>%s County</strong><br/>
      <b>%s</b><br/><br/>
      %s<br/><br/>
      <b>2022 Population:</b> %s<br/>
      <b>2023 Population:</b> %s<br/>
      <b>Percent Change:</b> %.2f%%
     </div>",
    map_data$NAME[i],
    map_data$headline[i],
    gsub("\n", "<br/>", map_data$capsule_narrative[i]),
    format(map_data$POPESTIMATE2022[i], big.mark = ","),
    format(map_data$POPESTIMATE2023[i], big.mark = ","),
    map_data$POPPERCENTCHANGE[i]
  ))
})
  ) |>
  addLegend(
    pal = pal,
    values = ~POPPERCENTCHANGE,
    opacity = 0.7,
    title = "Population % Change (20222023)",
    position = "bottomright"
  )

Workshop Wrap-Up and Conclusion

Congratulations! Youve now built a functional AI agent workflow in R that:

  • Extracts real-world data via APIs (e.g., U.S. Census Bureau),
  • Leverages a generative AI LLM to create narrative summaries automatically,
  • Integrates these narratives into interactive, data-rich maps, and
  • Demonstrates a practical approach for applying generative AI in regional economic analysis.

Key Takeaways

  1. Automating Insight Generation: Youve seen how AI agents can save time by producing clear, interpretable narratives from complex datasets.
  2. Structured Prompting Matters: Carefully designed prompts guide the AI to produce outputs that are relevant, accurate, and consistent.
  3. Bringing Data to Life: Combining AI-generated narratives with visualizations enhances communication and storytelling.
  4. Process Over Tool: Understanding the workflow is more important than any single API or package; the same principles can be applied to other datasets and domains.

Next Steps

  • Experiment with other data sources and use cases relevant to your work.
  • Refine prompts and narratives to suit different audiences, from policymakers to the public.
  • Explore additional mapping and visualization techniques to further enrich your outputs.
  • Consider ethical and responsible use of generative AI, especially when communicating insights derived from public data.

Thank you for participating! We hope this workshop has equipped you with practical tools, new perspectives, and inspiration to leverage generative AI in your regional economic work.
